                                <support>Textblock of cross-grained, externally sized and polished,
                                    ivoury-coloured <material>paper</material> probably handmade in
                                    the <placeName cert="high"
                                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208"
                                        key="place_7000208">Indian subcontinent</placeName> with ~8
                                    laid lines per cm and no discernible chain lines.</support>
                                <extent>
                                    <measure unit="page" quantity="838">838 pages, 3 flyleaves (pp. ii + 838 + i)</measure>.-->
                                    <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                                        <height>255</height>
                                        <width>153</width>
                                    </dimensions>
                                    <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                                        <height>203</height>
                                        <width>104</width>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </extent>
                                <foliation xml:id="original">Paginated in Hindu-Arabic numerals on the top-centres of the pages until <locus>page 220</locus>.</foliation>
                                <foliation xml:id="modern">Paginated in modern pencilled Arabic numerals on the upper corners throughout, albeit with gaps.</foliation>
                                <collation>Undetermined, possibly quaternions throughtout. <catchwords>Catchwords written on the lower-left corners of the b sides throughout, albeit some trimmed.</catchwords></collation>
                                <condition>Handle with extreme caution, ideally with the assistance of a conservator. Text in very poor condition, with folio <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus> detached, extensive water and mould, grime, and many pages stuck together. </condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout columns="1" ruledLines="17" n="mistara">Written in 1 column with 17 lines per page. Ruled with a <hi rend="italic">misṭarah</hi> hand guide.</layout>                  
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>                                   
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote scope="major" script="nasta_liq" medium="ink">
                                Written in clear <material>black</material> nasta‘līq with <material>vermilion</material> subheaders.
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
                        <additions/>
                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding notBefore="1800" notAfter="1900">
                                <p>European-style single-flexible sewning on five cord supports. Endpapers added, and edges trimmed. Endbands sewn (now missing). Covered in half sheepskin <material>leather</material> with 'Old Dutch' patterned marbled paper sides.
                                Subsequently repaired with a semi-limp vellum jacket, a portion of which remains attached to the <locus from="Upper_cover" to="Upper_cover">right board exterior</locus>. </p>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                        <accMat>Two documents, a binding request form accompanied by a letter from Librarian <persName role="crp" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/88892001" key="person_88892001">Edward Robertson</persName> to Manchester bookbinding firm <orgName role="bdr" key="">H. Richards &amp; Sons</orgName>.</accMat>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>Probably India, <origPlace>India</origPlace> undated, but completed prior to <origDate cert="high" calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1750" notAfter="1817-04-21">21 Apr. 1817 CE.</origDate> as per a note on page <locus>60</locus>.</origin>
                        <provenance><p>The circumstances under which this volume arrived in Britain remain unclear, but the marginal notes indicate that a British student of Persian previously owned the volume.</p></provenance>
                        <provenance><p>Subsequently acquired by <persName role="fmo" key="person_12428346" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/12428346">Moses Gaster (1856–1939)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                            
                            
                        <acquisition>
